Why always using fr style dates?
As mentioned in the comments above, it is used because `fr` is one of the locales (which I picked randomly) that uses an offset (`UTC±X` format) with `timeZoneName: 'short'` parameter in all the time zones.
Other locales, like `en-GB`, use abbreviations (e.g., `EET` for `Europe/Vilnius`, `CET` for `Europe/Oslo`, etc.) which is not what we need:
```js
Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-US', { timeZone: `America/Cayman`, timeZoneName: 'short' }).formatToParts(new Date()).pop();
// result: EST
Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-GB', { timeZone: `Europe/Oslo`, timeZoneName: 'short' }).formatToParts(new Date()).pop()
// result: CET

Intl.DateTimeFormat('fr', { timeZone: `America/Cayman`, timeZoneName: 'short' }).formatToParts(new Date()).pop();
// result: UTC-5
Intl.DateTimeFormat('fr', { timeZone: `Europe/Oslo`, timeZoneName: 'short' }).formatToParts(new Date()).pop();
// result: UTC+1
```

Ideally, we should use `timeZoneName: 'shortOffset'` (so all the locales, including `en-US`, would return a proper `UTC/GMT±X` offset and not some kind of abbreviation) but we can't do this today because in Node.js this parameter is only supported from `v17.0.0`. While `timeZoneName: 'short'` is supported from `v0.12.0`.

Nonetheless, there shouldn't be anything wrong in using a fixed locale (in this case `fr`) because all the offsets should be the same in all the locales.

Basically, `timeZoneName: 'short'` acts indentical as `timeZoneName: 'shortOffset'` in `fr` locale:
```js
Intl.DateTimeFormat('fr', { timeZone: 'Europe/Oslo', timeZoneName: 'short' }).formatToParts(new Date()).pop();
// result: UTC+1

 Intl.DateTimeFormat('fr', { timeZone: 'Europe/Oslo', timeZoneName: 'shortOffset' }).formatToParts(new Date()).pop();
// result: UTC+1
```

