There are some things to consider about this approach:
1. There could arguably be cases where `NavigationException` _should_ be treated as an error (e.g., if it's thrown during interactive rendering). It might be preferable to allow error boundaries to handle `NavigationException`s during interactive rendering, but not static server rendering. To support this, we could alternatively update the `ErrorBoundaryBase` implementation to ignore `NavigationException` instances when prerendering.
2. Since `NavigationException` is not `sealed`, someone could extend it to create more exceptions that bypass error boundaries. I'm not totally sure why someone would do this, but if we see it as a potential antipattern and want to proactively discourage it, we could update this to:
    ```csharp
    if (error.GetType() == typeof(NavigationException))
    {
        HandleException(error);
        return;
    }
    ```
1. It's good to think this through, but TBH it's not clear to me that we need to introduce further distinctions between interactive and static rendering on this behavior. Unless there's a known use case, that is.
2. That's a great thing to anticipate. I think the only reason for subclassing `NavigationException` is if you're also implementing a custom rendering platform, and you want a way to extend the meaning of "navigation" on your platform with other fields/flags (and in that case, you don't want it to trigger an error boundary - it would just be an obscure bug you probably didn't realise you caused). People can't really subclass it for arbitrary non-navigation-related reasons because the framework is still going to catch their subclass and use it to perform a navigation, hence it seems unlikely the feature could be misused.

So in summary my guess is your existing design/implementation is already the best design. Unless you know of more reasons we should anticipate misuse/problems.
> I think the only reason for subclassing NavigationException is if you're also implementing a custom rendering platform

Actually even that use case doesn't really make sense to me now I think about it. It would have to be a new custom SSR rendering platform, not an interactive one. And who's doing that?

So if we wanted to be super risk-averse, we could have logic like:

```cs
if (error is NavigationException)
{
  if (error.GetType() == typeof(NavigationException))
  {
      HandleException(error);
      return;
  }
  else
  {
      throw new InvalidOperationException("We don't know what you're trying to do, but stop doing it");
  }
}
```
> So in summary my guess is your existing design/implementation is already the best design. Unless you know of more reasons we should anticipate misuse/problems.

Yeah, I agree - I don't anticipate that either of the points I brought up will become real problems, but I figured it might be a good idea to bring them up in case anyone thought otherwise. There's room to revise this in the future if we feel the need to as well.

What do you think about having the string "all" as a possible value for this param to replace `module_ctx.use_all_repos` (similarly for dev deps)?

The obvious downside is the weird typing, but the advantage of this is that we remove some mental burden and _if_ we were to have other fields on ExtensionMetadata later on, it's more composable.
That's an interesting idea. 

My first reaction is that I would expect this to *increase* the mental burden in the main situations in which I expect `use_all_repos` to be used: Module extensions that are essentially WORKSPACE macros. For those, I find

```starlark
return module_ctx.use_all_repos()
```

significantly less loaded than (assuming we allow omitting `root_module_direct_dev_deps` in this case)

```starlark
return module_ctx.extension_metadata(root_module_direct_deps = "all")
```

However, this concern could be alleviated by a helper function such as the following living outside core Bazel:

```starlark
def as_module_extension(macro, *, dev_dependency = False):
    def _ext_impl(module_ctx):
        macro()
        if hasattr(module_ctx, "extension_metadata"):
            return module_ctx.extension_metadata(
                root_module_direct_deps = None if dev_dependency else "all",
                root_module_direct_dev_deps = "all" if dev_dependency else None,
            )

    return module_extension(_ext_impl)
```
yeah. now the question is where to put this as_module_extension thing :)

also notable that use_all_repos is implementable in terms of the "all" thing, but not vice versa. Mostly due to the composability point.
Result of an offline discussion: We will go for `"all"`, but realize a wrapper for the simple use case of a WORKSPACE macro either in skylib or Bazel itself.

