Added the following unit test:
``` csharp
[Test]
public void TryGetSymbol_FromTicker_WithConflictingSymbolWithCustomDataSuffix()
{
    var ticker = "My-Ticker";
    var symbol = Symbol.Create(ticker, SecurityType.Equity, Market.USA);
    SymbolCache.Set(ticker, symbol);

    var customTicker = $"{ticker}.CustomDataTypeName";
    var customSymbol = Symbol.Create(customTicker, SecurityType.Base, Market.USA, baseDataType: typeof(Bitcoin));
    SymbolCache.Set(customTicker, customSymbol);

    Symbol fetchedSymbol;
    Assert.IsTrue(SymbolCache.TryGetSymbol(ticker, out fetchedSymbol));
    Assert.AreEqual(symbol, fetchedSymbol);

    Symbol fetchedCustomSymbol;
    Assert.IsTrue(SymbolCache.TryGetSymbol(customTicker, out fetchedCustomSymbol));
    Assert.AreEqual(customSymbol, fetchedCustomSymbol);
}
```

Now... you bring up a _really_ great point. Consider `AddData<T>("SPY")` and `AddEquity("SPY")` -- using the `string` `"SPY"` will _always_ resolve to the equity and _never_ to the custom data type, which would require you to specify `"SPY.TypeName"`. This is another potentially breaking change, although I'm not sure how common this collision is in practice.

In the case where there is no potential for collision, say `AddData<T>("SPY")` and `AddEquity("Not-SPY")`, using `string` `"SPY"` will resolve to the only potential match, which would be `"SPY.TypeName"` since there is not entry that exactly matches `"SPY"`.

